**Describe the bug**
I'm using ONNX Runtime in a custom class, following the issue https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4131 I was able to make it work when the execution provider is CPU, **but fails using CUDA**.

**I can run properly the program using CUDA as execution provider with no crashes when I'm not using it inside my custom class** (so, without using pointers for session and env)

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Windows 11 Pro - 10.0.22000 Build 22000:
- ONNX Runtime installed from [github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/releases/tag/v1.9.0](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/releases/tag/v1.9.0):
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.9.0
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): using Qt, **Desktop_Qt_6_2_0_MSVC2019_64bit**
- Program compiled with: Microsoft Visual C++ Compiler 16.10.31515.178 (amd64)
- CUDA/cuDNN version:
```
nvcc: NVIDIA (R) Cuda compiler driver
Copyright (c) 2005-2021 NVIDIA Corporation
Built on Sun_Aug_15_21:18:57_Pacific_Daylight_Time_2021
Cuda compilation tools, release 11.4, V11.4.120
Build cuda_11.4.r11.4/compiler.30300941_0
```
- GPU model and memory: Quadro T2000

**To Reproduce**
This is what I have in the class header:
```
    //    https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4131
    std::unique_ptr<Ort::Session> session = nullptr;
    std::unique_ptr<Ort::Env> env = nullptr;
```

And this is the implementation:
```
    Ort::SessionOptions session_options;
    OrtCUDAProviderOptions cuda_options;
    cuda_options.device_id = 0;
    session_options.AppendExecutionProvider_CUDA(cuda_options);
    session_options.SetGraphOptimizationLevel(GraphOptimizationLevel::ORT_ENABLE_EXTENDED );

    auto env_local = std::make_unique<Ort::Env>(ORT_LOGGING_LEVEL_WARNING, "test");
    env = std::move(env_local);
    auto session_local = std::make_unique<Ort::Session>(*env, model_filename, session_options);
    session = move(session_local);
```

Running the inference in this way:
```
    std::cout << "Starting inference!" << std::endl;
    session->Run(Ort::RunOptions{ nullptr },
                input_names.data(),  input_tensors.data(),  input_tensors.size(),
                output_names.data(), output_tensors.data(), output_tensors.size());
    std::cout << "End inference!" << std::endl;
```

When I run the inference with CUDA, the program outputs "End inference!" then hangs and is terminated (The process was ended forcefully.)
I'm able to call `n` times in sequence the funcion that runs the inference and it outputs properly "End inference!" `n` times, but finally crashes in the same way.

For example:
```
    std::cout << "first time" << std::endl;
    onnx_inference.RunTheInference(blob);
    std::cout << "second time" << std::endl;
    onnx_inference.RunTheInference(blob);
    std::cout << "third time" << std::endl;
    onnx_inference.RunTheInference(blob);
```

I'm also able to show the result of the inference using openCV GUI, but finally the program crashes with this message:

> `[process exited with code 3221225477 (0xc0000005)]`


**Expected behavior**
The program should `terminate with code 0`.

The program works fine commenting out this line:
`session_options.AppendExecutionProvider_CUDA(cuda_options);`
